In [[demonology]], '''Morax''' is a Demon, Great Earl, and President of [[Hell]], having thirty (thirty-two, according to other authors) legions of [[demon]]s under his command. He teaches [[Astronomy]] and all other liberal sciences, and gives good and wise [[Familiar spirit|familiars]] that know the virtues of all herbs and precious stones. This profile of the demon can be seen in Pseudomonarchia Daemonum (Johann Weyer, 1577) as well as in Goetia (S.L. MacGregor Mathers, 1904).

He is depicted both as a man with the head of a bull, as well as a bull with the head of a man.

It has been proposed that Morax is related to the Minotaur which Dante places in Hell (''Inferno'', Canto xii). See Fred Gettings, Dictionary of Demons (1988)

His name seems to come from [[Latin]] 'morax', that delays, that [[wiktionary:Stops|stops]].

''Other spellings'': Foraii, Marax, Farax.

